HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1474
By Reeves
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend the 21st District Recovery
Court on the occasion of its twenty-fifth
anniversary.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly take great pleasure in honoring
those programs and institutions that work to improve the lives of citizens and strengthen
communities across this State; and
WHEREAS, one such exemplary program is the 21st District Recovery Court, which is
celebrating its twenty-fifth anniversary, having been established in 2001 to address the critical
intersection of addiction and the criminal justice system; and
WHEREAS, the mission of the 21st District Recovery Court is to end the cycle of
addiction and crime in the community by providing accountability and compassion to nonviolent
offenders, thereby saving lives, restoring families, and promoting safer and more productive
communities; and
WHEREAS, the program was founded through the leadership and vision of the
Honorable Timothy L. Easter, the Honorable Donald P. Harris, and coordinator Gayle Moyer
Harris, whose dedication laid the groundwork for a model of justice rooted in both responsibility
and rehabilitation; and
WHEREAS, following its establishment, the organization received nonprofit status in
April 2002, and in August of that year, the first participants were admitted into its comprehensive
two-year program; and
WHEREAS, since its inception, more than 300 individuals have participated in the
Recovery Court program, with more than 200 successfully graduating; and
HJR1474
016926
- 1 -

WHEREAS, the effectiveness of the 21st District Recovery Court is evidenced by its
strong outcomes, including a proven record of reducing recidivism, saving taxpayer resources,
and fostering long-term recovery among its participants; and
WHEREAS, in the past five years, approximately ninety percent of participants have
maintained full- or part-time employment, while many have regained custody of their children
and re-established relationships with their families; others have pursued educational
advancement through earning a GED, high school diploma, or higher education opportunities;
and
WHEREAS, most significantly, a substantial majority of graduates continue to lead
stable, productive lives well beyond their time in the program, reflecting the enduring impact of
the Recovery Court's work; and
WHEREAS, the success of the 21st District Recovery Court stands as a testament to the
power of accountability, compassion, and community support in transforming lives and
strengthening the fabric of Tennessee; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor and commend the 21st District Recovery Court on the occasion
of its twenty-fifth anniversary, celebrating its many contributions to the well-being of individuals,
families, and communities, and extend to all those associated with the program our best wishes
for continued success in the years to come.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
